{"data":{"post":{"id":"d2014ad8-62ff-5e02-8db6-2a29a2928a6b","html":"<p>If John Lennon’s song Imagine can be transformed into a visual language, it would be something like this Disarm exhibition at the Lisson gallery. I think Pedro Reyes’ weapons-cum-musical instruments really tune into what is probably the closest thing I’ve ever seen visual arts do to call for peace. In Disarm, <strong>Pedro fashions destroyed weapons into mechanical musical instruments</strong> and transforms them into objects with a positive message. And it’s not bad too that these instruments are also functional and can be played live or automated by a computer. </p>\n<p>There’s probably too much to take in here – in fact, I had to deal with a spectrum of emotions when I saw Disarm – as if I was listening to some affecting music. First, as sculptural pieces, they all look beautiful – <strong>they are a re-imagining of how musical instruments should be in the 21st century</strong> and even without the music, they would have probably been able to stand alone as fine-tuned beautifully-crafted pieces of sculpture.</p>\n<p>\n  <figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n  \n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/Pedro-Reyes_Disarm_Installation_jormgm-6144b75804c8d2edec2547179636bdc3-55fd7.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; null; max-width: 640px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 75%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"Pedro Reyes_Disarm_Installation\"\n        title=\"Pedro Reyes. Disarm Mechanized 2012. Recycled Metal. Installation comprising of 8 mechanized instruments\"\n        src=\"/static/Pedro-Reyes_Disarm_Installation_jormgm-6144b75804c8d2edec2547179636bdc3-55fd7.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/Pedro-Reyes_Disarm_Installation_jormgm-6144b75804c8d2edec2547179636bdc3-e81c0.jpg 200w,\n/static/Pedro-Reyes_Disarm_Installation_jormgm-6144b75804c8d2edec2547179636bdc3-8e8ea.jpg 400w,\n/static/Pedro-Reyes_Disarm_Installation_jormgm-6144b75804c8d2edec2547179636bdc3-55fd7.jpg 640w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n  <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Pedro Reyes. Disarm Mechanized 2012. Recycled Metal. Installation comprising of 8 mechanized instruments</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n      </p>\n<p>\n  <figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n  \n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/Pedro-Reyes_Disarm_Harpanet_psx62g-c6960ca10d81f4a81b4909c6ee5213ae-55fd7.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; null; max-width: 640px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 75%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"Pedro Reyes_Disarm_Harpanet\"\n        title=\"Pedro Reyes. Disarm Harpanet 2013. Metal\"\n        src=\"/static/Pedro-Reyes_Disarm_Harpanet_psx62g-c6960ca10d81f4a81b4909c6ee5213ae-55fd7.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/Pedro-Reyes_Disarm_Harpanet_psx62g-c6960ca10d81f4a81b4909c6ee5213ae-e81c0.jpg 200w,\n/static/Pedro-Reyes_Disarm_Harpanet_psx62g-c6960ca10d81f4a81b4909c6ee5213ae-8e8ea.jpg 400w,\n/static/Pedro-Reyes_Disarm_Harpanet_psx62g-c6960ca10d81f4a81b4909c6ee5213ae-55fd7.jpg 640w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n  <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Pedro Reyes. Disarm Harpanet 2013. Metal</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n      </p>\n<p>Second – and this is where it really gets bloody – the material used to craft these pieces all came from firearms, revolvers, shot guns, machine guns – all killer weapons – and** just thinking what’s behind its bloodstained journey is enough to make you feel some jolt in the senses**. These are weapons offered to Pedro by the Mexican government who’ve confiscated these items. Crushed and steamrolled by military tanks, these weapons find their tragic end to their tragic journey.</p>\n<p>Then they get resurrected into these musical instruments enough to rid it of its dark past. <strong>How Pedro was able to transform these deadly machines into playable and functional instruments is a true feat</strong>. It bodes well that Pedro was trained in architecture so he has this vision of creating art that has utility. In a video featured also at Lisson gallery, I was able to see how he and his team hammers away these weapons of war into a flute, a drum, a harp creating beautiful music from something that used to deadly.</p>\n<p>For Pedro “[It] was more than physical. It’s important to consider that many lies were taken with these weapons; as if a sort of exorcism was taking place, the music expelled the demons they held as well as being a requiem for lives lost.”</p>\n<p>\n  <figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n  \n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/Pe